# EVAIX App Integration & Selection Guide

## 1. Core Architectural Directives
EVAIX is an agentic, self-bootstrapping Desktop Environment built on Fedora. When selecting, designing, or integrating applications into the EVAIX monorepo, AI agents must strictly adhere to the following principles:

*   **No Databases:** Do not introduce Postgres, SQLite, MongoDB, or any traditional RDBMS. All state, configurations, and schedules must be serialized into human- and LLM-readable JSON flat files.
*   **TypeScript-First:** Prioritize pure TypeScript packages within the monorepo over pre-compiled native Linux apps or closed web apps. Code must be ingestible, type-safe, and reusable across other platforms.
*   **Agentic Transparency:** Every app must expose its core functions via a lightweight Model Context Protocol (MCP) server or a direct JSON API so the AgentRuntime can manipulate it. 
*   **UI Constraints:** The frontend relies on React and MUI. UIs should be fast, utilitarian, and distraction-free. Avoid flashy animations or bloated CSS frameworks.

## 2. The App Priority Matrix
When deciding what applications to build or integrate, evaluate them against this matrix.

| Priority | Category | Integration Standard | Example |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **P0** | **Base OS Utilities** | Typescript Monorepo Package + JSON State | Terminal, Browser, Weekly Scheduler. |
| **P1** | **Development** | NativeNode Wrapper + MCP Bridge | Code editors, terminal debuggers. |
| **P2** | **File/System Management** | Typescript + Node FS Module | VFS explorers, system resource monitors (mapped to JSON). |
| **P3** | **External Comms** | WebNode (iframe) + MCP Bridge | Chat interfaces, email clients. |

## 3. Implementation Standard: The Weekly Scheduler
*Reference this standard when building the EVAIX calendar/scheduler.*

**The UI Layer:**
Use an MUI-compatible weekly time-grid component. It must support drag-and-drop and snap to a weekly matrix, similar to native Android schedulers. 

**The Storage Layer:**
The UI saves events to a local `scheduler.json` file in the following strict format. Agents will read and write to this file to schedule automations:

```json
{
  "jobs": [
    {
      "id": "job_01",
      "cron": "0 9 * * 1",
      "intent": "Review U1 Silvernale clearing parameters with small contract director of harvesting",
      "automationPayload": {
        "agent": "jules-orchestrator",
        "action": "prepare_briefing_doc"
      }
    }
  ]
}